Determining Unfairness in Medicaid Reimbursement Rates

Between Idaho and the Nation

by Robert Barnett on November 26, 2023

Background

Medicaid has a reputation for underpaying healthcare providers for covered services. In a blog article from The Commonwealth Fund titled "Medicaid Reimbursement Rates Are a Racial Justice Issue", the authors discuss how reimbursement rates affect access and quality of care for underprivileged groups. They highlight that Medicaid reimbursement rates are significantly lower than Medicare and commercial insurance rates which creates a financial disincentive for providers to accept Medicaid patients which affects availability and quality of care. It draws many connections between Medicaid's low reimbursement rates and low quality of care.

A lawsuit was filed in 2021 by the National Association of Chain Drug Stores (NACDS), National Community Pharmacists Association (NCPA), and the Washington State Pharmacy Association versus the Secretary of the United States Department of Health and Human Services (HHS), and the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS). The plaintiffs claim that Medicaid does not adequatly reimburse pharmacies for the services they provide to beneficiaries and that their reimbursement rates are the lowest in the country which violates federal law. They allege that the rates are below their actual costs which has caused significant harm to rural and independent pharmacies. Their case particularly focuses on the dispensing fee portion of their reimbursement rates, which covers costs associated with dispensing a medication, such as payroll, utilities, rent, supplies, etc.

Medicaid underpayment has been a long concern in the legislative landscape as well. In 2006, CMS proposed a rule to implement provisions of the Deficit Reduction Act that would reduce Medicaid reimbursements for prescriptions. The rule would redefine the cost basis for reimbursements. HHS forecasted that the change would adversely affect revenue for small pharmacies in low-income areas where the concentrations of Medicaid beneficiaries was high. HHS advised that small pharmacies purchase lower-cost drugs to mitigate the burden. However, that was already a best practice among all pharmacies. HHS also released a report finding that 19 of the 25 highest expenditure drugs would result in underpayments under the new rule. Pharmacy groups attempted to work with lawmakers to draft revisions to change the cost-basis to a metric that was tangible for pharmacies, but the CMS administrator dismissed concerns in favor of waiting to see how things turned out.

In my peronal experience working in Idaho pharmacies, I have had many opportunities to examine rates of reimbursement from many payors, including Medicaid. There have been many times that I have had to challenge reimbursements that were below cost. In many situations, the discrepancies in pricing were the result of Idaho's Medicaid program using outdated database information. In one case, a medication was unavailable due to a national backorder except for one NDC. As that price increased, Medicaid continued to reimburse at the outdated rate. These experiences are the initiators of my concern for Medicaid underpayments.

Investigation

The two datasets were obtained from Medicaid's website as publically available datasets. The NADAC dataset contains information used to expand the information in the Drug Utilization dataset based on NDC as a key. The exploration of the dataset will filter out unnecessary data and then compare reimbursement rates to evaluate a null hypothesis.

Definitions

The following terms appear within the datasets in this investigation:

  • ndc - National Drug Code. A concatenation of three codes that indicate the manufacturer, the drug, and the package size. It is a unique identifier of a product offering.
  • state - The two-letter acronym for a state in the United States of America. Additionally, XX is used to indicate the nation as a whole.
  • product_name - The common name of the drug.
  • units_reimbursed - The total number of units, based on unit of measurement, that were dispensed.
  • number_of_prescriptions - The total number of prescriptions that were filled for the NDC.
  • total_amount_reimbursed - The total value of reimbursement paid to the pharmacy.
  • NDC Description - in the NADAC table, this is the full product name, which includes the drug name, strength, and dosage form. It becomes renamed to drug.
  • Pricing_Unit - This is the unit of measurement, which can be EA, ML, OR GM for eaches, volume, or mass, respectively. This investigation will omit volume and mass dispensings since those can have variable rates or reimbursement (either full pack or partial pack payments).
  • Classification_for_Rate_Setting - This separates between brand or generic medications. They are typically priced on two separate scales. If a generic was reimbursed at the same scale as a brand drug, it could become cost-prohibitive to stock. Conversely, if a brand was priced on the same scale as a generic, it could become astronomical in price.



Hypothesis

A Z-test uses a Z-score to determine if two means are different. A Z-score measures how many standard deviations that a sample mean deviates fomr the population mean. If our sample Z-score (Idaho's rate of reimbursment) is outside our Z-score critical boundary, then the null hypothesis will be rejected.

This investigation will explore if a difference exists in the reimbursement rates of medications paid by Idaho's Medicaid program compared to all Medicaid programs in the nation. The top 5 dispensed brand name medications and the top 5 dispensed generic medications, by NDC, will be evaluated based on their reimbursement per unit. Reimbursement per unit measures the amount paid per tablet. The data will be evaluated on a single NDC per drug since pricing can vary greatly between manufacturers. Medicaid subscribes to a pricing database (such as Medispan or First Databank) which does not vary pricing by region. This database is used for calculating reimbursements.

The Z-score test will be applied to two subsets of data. One subset compares the Z-scores for branded drugs and the other subset for generic drugs.

  • Null Hypothesis: There is no significant difference in reimbursement rates between Idaho and the nation.
  • Alternate Hypothesis: There is a significant difference in reimbursement rates between Idaho and the nation.
  • = 0.05
  • Z-Critical = 1.96

Cleaning the Data

Drug Utilization Table

  • The column ndc is int64 type. NDCs (national drug codes) are normally an 11-digit code created as a concatenation of a 5-digit labeler code, 4-digit product code, and 2-digit package size code.
  • In order to join the NADAC table to the Drug Utilization table on the NDC column, the NDC codes must match.
  • The column will be cast as string then filled with the missing leading zeros.
  • In order to compare the reimbursement data, the amount reimbursed cannot be directly compared due to varying volumes per state. The amount reimbursed will be divided by units reimbursed to create a calculated field of a standardized reimbursement_per_unit. The related fields are float64 type and are appropriate for this operation.
  • Some quarters may be missing data which is evidenced by the NaN values. Since pricing can adjust from quarter to quarter based on market fluctations, then proper comparisons should be made within a particular quarter.
  • Drop rows containing NaN values and then compare the length of each quarter to find the most complete quarter to compare.

NADAC Table

  • The column NDC is int64 type. As such, it has lost the leading zeroes. This will be cast as string and filled with leading zeros.
  • Rename NDC to ndc and NDC Description to drug
  • Remove duplicates of NDC
In[8]:
# cast ndc and NDC cols as strings
du['ndc'] = du['ndc'].astype(str)
nadac['NDC'] = nadac['NDC'].astype(str)

# fill in leading zeroes 
du['ndc'] = du['ndc'].str.zfill(11)
nadac['NDC'] = nadac['NDC'].str.zfill(11)

# rename columns
nadac = nadac.rename(columns={'NDC': 'ndc', 'NDC Description': 'drug'})

# create calculated reimbursement per unit column
du['reimbursement_per_unit'] = du['total_amount_reimbursed'] / du['units_reimbursed']

# drop unnecessary columns
du = du.drop(columns=['utilization_type', 'labeler_code','product_code','package_size', 'year', 
                      'suppression_used', 'medicaid_amount_reimbursed', 
                      'non_medicaid_amount_reimbursed'], axis=1)
nadac = nadac.drop(columns=['NADAC_Per_Unit', 'Effective_Date', 'Pharmacy_Type_Indicator', 
                            'Explanation_Code', 'Corresponding_Generic_Drug_NADAC_Per_Unit', 
                            'Corresponding_Generic_Drug_Effective_Date', 'As of Date'])
# drop duplicates of ndc
nadac = nadac.drop_duplicates(subset=['ndc'])

# Drop NaN entries
du = du.dropna()

Exploratory Data Analysis

In[10]:
# merge the drug info into the utilization info on ndc, many to one
data = du.merge(nadac, on='ndc', how='left', validate='m:1')

# select rows that are not for over-the-counter medications
data = data[data.OTC == 'N']

# selecting rows for the 1st quarter
data = data[data.quarter == 1]

# select only for 'EA' units of measure
data = data[data.Pricing_Unit == 'EA']

# create a calculated column for z-score of the reimbursement rates grouped by NDC
data['z_score_reimburse_rate'] = data.groupby(['ndc']).reimbursement_per_unit.transform(lambda x : zscore(x,ddof=1))

# separate brands and generics
data = data.dropna()
generic = data[data['Classification_for_Rate_Setting'] == 'G']
brand = data[data['Classification_for_Rate_Setting'] != 'G']

# z-scores filterd for ID and XX (nation)
id_generic = generic.loc[generic.state == 'ID'].sort_values(by=['z_score_reimburse_rate'], ascending=True)
id_brand = generic.loc[generic.state == 'XX'].sort_values(by=['z_score_reimburse_rate'], ascending=True)
xx_generic = brand.loc[brand.state == 'ID'].sort_values(by=['z_score_reimburse_rate'], ascending=True)
xx_brand = brand.loc[brand.state == 'XX'].sort_values(by=['z_score_reimburse_rate'], ascending=True)

# Functions
def plot_hist(top_5, bar_color):
    '''
    input a list of NDCs
    iterates over the list and constructs a dataframe of that NDC
    fetches the drug name from the nadac dataset
    constructs a histogram for 'reimbursement_per_unit' for each row of the iterated NDC
    where each row should represent one state
    '''
    for i in top_5:
        df = data[data.ndc == i]
        drug_name = nadac.loc[nadac['ndc'] == i, 'drug'].item()
        plt.hist(df['reimbursement_per_unit'], bins=14, color = bar_color, lw=2, ec='black')
        plt.title(f'Distribution of Reimbursement Rates for NDC: {i}\n{drug_name}')  
        plt.show()  

def multiplot_hist(top_5, max_lim):
    '''
    input a list of NDCs, max limit for x axis
    iterates over the list and fetches drug names
    sets the bin count and axis range based on max_lim
    creates a histogram for each NDC's reimbursement_per_unit on one plot
    '''
    drugs = []
    for i in top_5:
        drug_name = nadac.loc[nadac['ndc'] == i, 'drug'].item()
        drugs.append(drug_name)
    bins = np.linspace(0, max_lim, 200)
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[0]]['reimbursement_per_unit'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[0])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[1]]['reimbursement_per_unit'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[1])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[2]]['reimbursement_per_unit'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[2])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[3]]['reimbursement_per_unit'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[3])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[4]]['reimbursement_per_unit'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[4])
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.title('Distribution of Medicaid Reimbursement Rates for Selected Medications in Each State')
    plt.show()

def multiplot_z(top_5):
    '''
    input a list of NDCs
    iterates over the list and fetches drug names
    creates a histogram for each NDC's z-score on one plot
    '''
    drugs = []
    for i in top_5:
        drug_name = nadac.loc[nadac['ndc'] == i, 'drug'].item()
        drugs.append(drug_name)
    bins = np.linspace(-6, 6, 50)
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[0]]['z_score_reimburse_rate'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[0])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[1]]['z_score_reimburse_rate'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[1])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[2]]['z_score_reimburse_rate'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[2])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[3]]['z_score_reimburse_rate'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[3])
    plt.hist(data[data.ndc == top_5[4]]['z_score_reimburse_rate'], bins, alpha=0.5, label=drugs[4])
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.title('Distribution of Z-Scores for Medicaid Reimbursement Rates for Selected Medications in Each State')
    plt.show()

# z-score for generics vs idaho
for code, drug in zip(top5_generic, top5_generic_drugs):
    df = data[data.ndc == code]
    df_id = df.loc[df['state'] == 'ID']
    sd = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].std()
    mean = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].mean()
    median = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].median()
    minimum = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].min()
    maximum = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].max()
    id_value = df_id['reimbursement_per_unit'].item()
    z_score = (id_value - mean) / sd
    
    print(f'Evaluation of Z-Score for Idaho vs the Nation for Reimbursement Rates of\n{drug} (NDC: {code})')
    print(f'Standard Deviation: {sd}')
    print(f'Mean: {mean}')
    print(f'Median: {median}')
    print(f"Idaho's Reimbursement Rate: {id_value}")
    print(f'Z-Score: {z_score}\n')

In[22]:
# z-score for top dispensed brands vs idaho
for code, drug in zip(top5_brand, top5_brand_drugs):
    df = data[data.ndc == code]
    df_id = df.loc[df['state'] == 'ID']
    sd = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].std()
    mean = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].mean()
    median = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].median()
    minimum = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].min()
    maximum = df['reimbursement_per_unit'].max()
    id_value = df_id['reimbursement_per_unit'].item()
    z_score = (id_value - mean) / sd
    
    print(f'Evaluation of Z-Score for Idaho vs the Nation for Reimbursement Rates of\n{drug} (NDC: {code})')
    print(f'Standard Deviation: {sd}')
    print(f'Mean: {mean}')
    print(f'Median: {median}')
    print(f"Idaho's Reimbursement Rate: {id_value}")
    print(f'Z-Score: {z_score}\n')

Conclusion

The mean Z-scores for generic and brand reimbursement rates in Idaho for the 1st quarter of 2022, respectively, were:

  • 0.433
  • -0.003

The average Z-scores are lower than the Z-critical value of 1.96 so the null hypothesis is accepted that there is no significant difference in reimbursement rates between Idaho and the nation for both brand and generic drugs.

This analysis provided insights into the distribution of reimbursement rates across the nation. In the boxplot titled "Z-Scores for all Brand Medications in Each State", Kansas appears to have alarmingly low reimbursement rates. Other states may be able to benefit from similar analyses even though Idaho may not have directly benefited from it. Evidence exists to continue this study for other states.

Furthermore, the analysis could be useful for internal evaluation of a pharmacy's reimbursements compared to their state's average reimbursements. This could help a pharmacy root out procedural opportunities to optimize their billing practices to match their colleagues' best practices.
